\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
§ 5.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On one occasion the Blessed One was staying near Alavi on a spread of leaves
 by a cattle track in a simsapa forest.
 Then Hatthaka of Alavi, out roaming & rambling for exercise, saw the Blessed
 One sitting on a spread of leaves by the cattle track in the simsapa forest.
 On seeing him, he went to him and, on arrival, having bowed down to him,
 sat to one side.
 As he was sitting there he said to the Blessed One, "Lord, I hope the Blessed
 One has slept in ease."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes, young man.
 I have slept in ease.
 Of those in the world who sleep in ease, I am one."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"But cold, lord, is the winter night.
 The 'Between-the-Eights' is a time of snowfall.
 Hard is the ground trampled by cattle hooves.
 Thin is the spread of leaves.
 Sparse are the leaves in the trees.
 Thin are your ochre robes.
 And cold blows the Verambha wind.
 Yet still the Blessed One says, 'Yes, young man.
 I have slept in ease.
 Of those in the world who sleep in ease, I am one.'"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"In that case, young man, I will question you in return.
 Answer as you see fit.
 Now, what do you think: Suppose a householder or householder's son has
 a house with a gabled roof, plastered inside & out, draft-free, with close-fitt
ing door & windows shut against the wind.
 Inside he has a horse-hair couch spread with a long-fleeced coverlet, a
 white wool coverlet, an embroidered coverlet, a rug of kadali-deer hide,
 with a canopy above, & red cushions on either side.
 And there a lamp would be burning, and his four wives, with their many
 charms, would be attending to him.
 Would he sleep in ease, or not? Or how does this strike you?"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes, lord, he would sleep in ease.
 Of those in the world who sleep in ease, he would be one."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"But what do you think, young man.
 Might there arise in that householder or householder's son any bodily fevers
 or fevers of mind born of passion so that — burned with those passion-born
 fevers — he would sleep miserably?"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes, lord."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"As for those passion-born fevers — burned with which the householder or
 householder's son would sleep miserably — that passion has been abandoned
 by the Tathagata, its root destroyed, made like a palmyra stump, deprived
 of the conditions of development, not destined for future arising.
 Therefore he sleeps in ease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Now, what do you think, young man.
 Might there arise in that householder or householder's son any bodily fevers
 or fevers of mind born of aversion so that — burned with those aversion-born
 fevers — he would sleep miserably?"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes, lord."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"As for those aversion-born fevers — burned with which the householder or
 householder's son would sleep miserably — that aversion has been abandoned
 by the Tathagata, its root destroyed, made like a palmyra stump, deprived
 of the conditions of development, not destined for future arising.
 Therefore he sleeps in ease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Now, what do you think, young man.
 Might there arise in that householder or householder's son any bodily fevers
 or fevers of mind born of delusion so that — burned with those delusion-born
 fevers — he would sleep miserably?"
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yes, lord."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"As for those delusion-born fevers — burned with which the householder or
 householder's son would sleep miserably — that delusion has been abandoned
 by the Tathagata, its root destroyed, made like a palmyra stump, deprived
 of the conditions of development, not destined for future arising.
 Therefore he sleeps in ease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Always, always, he sleeps in ease: the brahman totally unbound, who doesn't
 adhere to sensual pleasures, who's without acquisitions & cooled.
 Having cut all ties & subdued fear in the heart, calmed, he sleeps in ease,
 having reached peace of awareness."
\end_layout

