\begin_layout Standard
MN 1: Mulapariyaya Sutta — The Root Sequence {M i 1} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this difficult but important sutta the Buddha reviews in depth one of
 the most fundamental principles of Buddhist thought and practice: namely,
 that there is no thing — not even Nibbana itself — that can rightly be
 regarded as the source from which all phenomena and experience emerge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 2: Sabbasava Sutta — All the Fermentations {M i 6} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha teaches seven methods for eliminating from the mind the deeply
 rooted defilements (sensuality, becoming, views, and ignorance) that obstruct
 the realization of Awakening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 4: Bhaya-bherava Sutta — Fear & Terror {M i 16} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What would it take to live in solitude in the wilderness, completely free
 of fear? The Buddha explains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 7: Vatthupama Sutta — The Simile of the Cloth {M i 36} [Nyanaponika].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a simple simile the Buddha illustrates the difference between a defiled
 mind and a pure mind.
 [BB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 8: Sallekha Sutta — The Discourse on Effacement {M i 40} [Nyanaponika].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha explains how the unskillful qualities in the heart can be eradicated
 through meditation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 9: Sammaditthi Sutta — Right View {M i 46} [Ñanamoli/Bodhi | Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discussion of right view demonstrating how the four noble truths, dependent
 co-arising, and the knowledge that ends mental fermentation all build on
 the basic dichotomy between skillful and unskillful action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 10: Satipatthana Sutta — Frames of Reference/Foundations of Mindfulness
 {M i 55} [Nyanasatta | Soma | Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha's comprehensive practical instructions on the development of
 mindfulness as the basis for insight.
 [The text of this sutta is identical to that of the Maha-satipatthana Sutta
 (DN 22), except that the latter contains a more detailed exposition of
 the Four Noble Truths (sections 5a,b,c and d in part D of that version).]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 11: Cula-sihanada Sutta — The Shorter Discourse on the Lion's Roar {M
 i 63} [Ñanamoli/Bodhi].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha declares that only through practicing in accord with the Dhamma
 can Awakening be realized.
 His teaching is distinguished from those of other religions and philosophies
 through its unique rejection of all doctrines of self.
 [BB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 12: Maha-sihanada Sutta — The Great Discourse on the Lion's Roar {M i
 68} [Ñanamoli/Bodhi].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha expounds the ten powers of a Tathagata, his four kinds of intrepidity
, and other superior qualities which entitle him to "roar his lion's roar
 in the assemblies." [BB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 13: Maha-dukkhakkhandha Sutta — The Great Mass of Stress {M i 83} [Thanissaro
].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In deliciously graphic terms, the Buddha describes the allures and drawbacks
 of sensuality, physical form, and feeling.
 What better incentive could there be to escape samsara once and for all?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 14: Cula-dukkhakkhandha Sutta — The Lesser Mass of Stress {M i 91} [Thanissar
o].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What mental qualities must be abandoned in order to free oneself of greed,
 aversion, and delusion? Can painful austerities be used to purify oneself
 and burn away the karmic fruit of past misdeeds? Through skillful question-and-
answer dialogues with the lay follower Mahanama and with a group of Jain
 ascetics, the Buddha lays these questions to rest.
\end_layout

