\begin_layout Standard
A man looking to pick a fight asks the Buddha to explain his doctrine.
 The Buddha's answer mystifies not only the man, but also a number of monks.
 Ven.
 Maha Kaccana finally provides an explanation, and in the course of doing
 so explains what is needed to bring the psychological sources of conflict
 to an end.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 19: Dvedhavitakka Sutta — Two Sorts of Thinking {M i 114} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha recounts the events leading up to his Awakening, and describes
 his discovery that thoughts connected with sensuality, ill-will, and harmfulnes
s do not lead one to Awakening, while those connected with their opposites
 (renunciation, non ill-will, and harmlessness) do.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 20: Vitakkasanthana Sutta — The Relaxation of Thoughts {M i 118} [Thanissaro
 | Soma].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha offers five practical methods of responding wisely to unskillful
 thoughts (thoughts connected with desire, aversion, or delusion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 21: Kakacupama Sutta — The Simile of the Saw {M i 122} [Buddharakkhita
 (excerpt) | Thanissaro (excerpt)].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha tells the story of a wise slave who deliberately tests her mistress's
 patience.
 The Buddha invokes several memorable similes here to illustrate the correct
 way to develop patience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 22: Alagaddupama Sutta — The Snake Simile {M i 130} [Nyanaponika | Thanissaro
].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using two famous similes, the Buddha shows how the development of right
 view calls for the skillful application both of grasping and of letting-go.
 The sutta includes one of the Canon's most important expositions on the
 topic of not-self.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 24: Ratha-vinita Sutta — Relay Chariots {M i 145} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the simile of a set of relay chariots, Ven.
 Punna Mantaniputta explains the relationship of the factors of the path
 to the goal of the holy life.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 26: Ariyapariyesana Sutta — The Noble Search {M i 160} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of us spend a good part of our lives looking for happiness in all the
 wrong places.
 In this sutta the Buddha recounts the story of his own search and points
 out where a true and lasting happiness can be found.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 27: Cula-hatthipadopama Sutta — The Shorter Elephant Footprint Simile
 {M i 175} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At what point do you know for sure that the Buddha's awakening was genuine?
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 28: Maha-hatthipadopama Sutta — The Great Elephant Footprint Simile {M
 i 184} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explanation of the four noble truths, focusing on the aggregate of physical
 form and showing (1) how all the aggregates are interrelated and (2) how
 all four noble truths, together with the principle of dependent co-arising,
 are related to the aggregates.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 33: Maha-gopalaka Sutta — The Greater Cowherd Discourse {M i 220} [Thanissaro
].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eleven factors that are conducive to spiritual growth, and eleven that are
 obstructive.
 (Apart from the preamble, this sutta is identical to AN 11.18.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 34: Cula-gopalaka Sutta — The Shorter Discourse on the Cowherd (excerpt)
 {M i 225} [Olendzki].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this brief excerpt the Buddha urges his monks to cross over to the lasting
 safety of Nibbana.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 36: Maha-Saccaka Sutta — The Greater Discourse to Saccaka {M i 237} [Thanissa
ro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In response to an insinuating remark — that his ability not to be overcome
 by pleasure and pain is due simply to the fact that he never experienced
 any intense pleasures or pains — the Buddha recounts the pains he endured
 in his austerities, and the pleasures that attended the path to and his
 attainment of Awakening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 39: Maha-Assapura Sutta — The Greater Discourse at Assapura {M i 271}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With characteristic clarity and concision the Buddha outlines the full course
 of training by which a meditator may earn the right to call him- or herself
 a true contemplative.
 As presented here, the training begins with conscience and concern for
 the results of one's actions, and leads progressively onward through the
 cultivation of virtue, sense-restraint, moderation, wakefulness, mindfulness,
 alertness, the four jhanas, finally culminating in the realization of the
 insight knowledges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 41: Saleyyaka Sutta — The Brahmans of Sala {M i 285} [Ñanamoli].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha explains to a group of brahman householders how one's present
 actions — by body, speech, and mind — determine one's future fortune.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 43: Mahavedalla Sutta — The Greater Set of Questions-and-Answers {M i
 292} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Sariputta answers questions dealing with discernment, right view, and the
 higher meditative attainments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 44: Culavedalla Sutta — The Shorter Set of Questions-and-Answers {M i
 299} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dhammadinna the nun fields a series of Dhamma questions put to her by her
 former husband: questions on self-identification, cessation, penetration
 into the true nature of feeling, and the attainment of Nibbana.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 45: Cula-dhammasamadana Sutta — The Shorter Discourse on Taking on Practices
 {M i 305} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is something right because it feels right? [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 49: Brahma-nimantanika Sutta — The Brahma Invitation {M i 326} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha disarms two powerful antagonists through his profound understanding
 of the nature of consciousness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 52: Atthakanagara Sutta — To the Man from Atthakanagara {M i 349} [Thanissaro
].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Ananda describes eleven modes of practice that can lead to the Deathless.
 (Apart from the preamble, this sutta is identical to AN 11.17.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 53: Sekha-patipada Sutta — The Practice for One in Training {M i 353}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Consummate in clear-knowing and conduct" is a standard epithet for the
 Buddha.
 This sutta explains what it means, and shows that it can be used to describe
 an arahant as well.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 54: Potaliya Sutta — To Potaliya (excerpt) {M i 359} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using seven graphic similes for the drawbacks of sensual passions, the Buddha
 teaches Potaliya the householder what it means, in the discipline of a
 noble one, to have entirely cut off one's worldly affairs.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 57: Kukkuravatika Sutta — The Dog-duty Ascetic {M i 387} [Ñanamoli].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Act like a dog, and that's what you'll become.
 Choose your actions with care!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 58: Abhaya Sutta — To Prince Abhaya (On Right Speech) {M i 392} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha explains the criteria for determining whether or not something
 is worth saying.
 This discourse is a beautiful example of the Buddha's skill as teacher:
 not only does he talk about right speech, but he also demonstrates right
 speech in action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 59: Bahuvedaniya Sutta — Many Things to be Experienced/The Many Kinds
 of Feeling {M i 396} [Nyanaponika | Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha discusses the range of possible pleasures and joys, and concludes
 by advocating a pleasure that goes beyond feeling.
 [The text of this sutta is almost identical to that of SN 36.19.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 60: Apannaka Sutta — A Safe Bet {M i 400} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha explains to a group of householders how to navigate skillfully
 through the maze of wrong views.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 61: Ambalatthika-rahulovada Sutta — Advice to Rahula at Mango Stone {M
 i 414} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha admonishes his son, the novice Rahula, on the dangers of lying
 and stresses the importance of constant reflection on one's motives.
 (This is one of the suttas selected by King Asoka (r.
 270-232 BCE) to be studied and reflected upon frequently by all practicing
 Buddhists.
 See That the True Dhamma Might Last a Long Time: Readings Selected by King
 Asoka, by Thanissaro Bhikkhu.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 62: Maha-Rahulovada Sutta — The Greater Exhortation to Rahula {M i 420}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha delivers meditation instructions to his son, the novice Rahula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 63: Cula-Malunkyovada Sutta — The Shorter Instructions to Malunkya {M
 i 426} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Malunkyaputta threatens to disrobe unless the Buddha answers all his speculativ
e metaphysical questions.
 Using the famous simile of a man shot by a poison arrow, the Buddha reminds
 him that some questions are simply not worth asking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 66: Latukikopama Sutta — The Quail Simile {M i 447} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fetters are strong, not because of their own tensile strength, but because
 of the tenacity of our unwillingness to let them go.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 70: Kitagiri Sutta — At Kitagiri {M i 473} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discourse on the importance of conviction in the Buddhist path.
 Not only is conviction a prerequisite for listening to the Buddha's teachings
 with respect, but — as is shown by the unusual discussion here categorizing
 the types of noble disciples — it can underlie the practice all the way
 to the Deathless.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 72: Aggi-Vacchagotta Sutta — To Vacchagotta on Fire {M i 483} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha explains to a wanderer why he does not hold any speculative views.
 Using the simile of an extinguished fire he illustrates the destiny of
 the liberated being.
 [BB] [For more on the use of fire imagery in early Buddhist texts, see
 the book Mind Like Fire Unbound.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 74: Dighanakha Sutta — To LongNails {M i 497} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discussion of how to abandon doctrinaire views of radical acceptance,
 radical rejection, and any combination of the two.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 75: Magandiya Sutta — To Magandiya (excerpt) {M i 501} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this passage, the Buddha teaches a member of a hedonist sect about the
 nature of true pleasure and true health.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 78: Samana-Mundika Sutta — Mundika the Contemplative {M ii 22} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The highest attainment is not simply the abandoning of unskillful actions
 and a reversion to childlike harmlessness.
 It requires first developing skillful habits and skillful resolves, and
 then letting them go.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 82: Ratthapala Sutta — About Ratthapala {M ii 54} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A two-part story about the monk who, the Buddha said, was foremost among
 his disciples in ordaining on the power of pure conviction.
 In the first part of the story, Ratthapala deals with his parents' opposition
 to his ordaining, and their attempts, after ordination, to lure him back
 to lay life.
 In the second part, he recalls the four observations about the world that
 inspired him, as a healthy and wealthy young man, to ordain in the first
 place.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 86: Angulimala Sutta — About Angulimala {M ii 97} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A murderous bandit takes refuge in the Buddha, develops a heart of compassion,
 and becomes an arahant.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 87: Piyajatika Sutta — From One Who Is Dear {M ii 106} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
King Pasenadi of Kosala figures prominently in many discourses as a devout
 follower of the Buddha.
 In this discourse we learn how — thanks to Queen Mallika's astuteness —
 the king first became favorably disposed toward the Buddha.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 90: Kannakatthala Sutta — At Kannakatthala {M ii 125} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A case study in how social advantages can be a spiritual liability.
 The discussion focuses on the factors needed for release — attainable by
 all people, regardless of caste or race — while the gently satirical frame
 story shows how the life of a king, or any highly placed person, presents
 obstacles to developing those factors.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 95: Canki Sutta — With Canki (excerpt) {M ii 164} [Ñanamoli (excerpt)
 | Thanissaro (excerpt)].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A pompous brahman teenager questions the Buddha about safeguarding, awakening
 to, and attaining the truth.
 In the course of his answer, the Buddha describes the criteria for choosing
 a reliable teacher and how best to learn from such a person.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 97: Dhanañjani Sutta — To Dhanañjani {M ii 184} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A poignant story of a lay person whose welfare was of special concern to
 Ven.
 Sariputta, this discourse teaches two lessons in heedfulness.
 (1) If you're engaging in wrong livelihood, don't expect to escape the
 karmic consequences even if you're doing it to fulfil your duties to your
 family, parents, or friends.
 (2) Don't be satisfied with mundane levels of attainment in meditation
 when there is still more to be done.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 101: Devadaha Sutta — To Devadaha {M ii 214} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha refutes a Jain theory of kamma, which claims that one's present
 experience is determined solely by one's actions in past lives, and that
 the only way to undo the effects of past unskillful actions is to "burn
 them away" through severe practices of austerity.
 The Buddha here outlines one of his most important teachings on kamma:
 that it is both the results of past deeds and present actions that shape
 one's experience of the present.
 It is precisely this interaction of present and past that opens up the
 very possibility of Awakening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 105: Sunakkhatta Sutta — To Sunakkhatta {M ii 252} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha addresses the problem of meditators who overestimate their progress
 in meditation.
 The sutta ends with a warning: anyone who claims enlightenment as license
 for unrestrained behavior is like someone who fails to follow the doctor's
 orders after surgery, who knowingly drinks a cup of poison, or who deliberately
 extends a hand toward a deadly snake.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 106: Aneñja-sappaya Sutta — Conducive to the Imperturbable {M ii 261}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Advanced meditation instruction: how the fourth jhana and the formless attainmen
ts can be developed and used as a basis for the realization of Nibbana.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 107: Ganaka-Moggallana Sutta — The Discourse to Ganaka-Moggallana {M
 iii 1} [Horner].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha sets forth the gradual training of the Buddhist monk and describes
 himself as a "shower of the way." [BB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 108: Gopaka-Moggallana Sutta — Moggallana the Guardsman {M iii 7} [Thanissaro
].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Ananda explains how the Sangha maintains its unity and internal discipline
 after the passing away of the Buddha.
 [BB] Interestingly, this sutta also shows that early Buddhist practice
 had no room for many practices that developed in later Buddhist traditions,
 such as appointed lineage holders, elected ecclesiastical heads, or the
 use of mental defilements as a basis for concentration practice.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 109: Maha-punnama Sutta — The Great Full-moon Night Discourse {M iii
 15} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A thorough discussion of issues related to the five aggregates.
 Toward the end of the discussion, a monk thinks that he has found a loophole
 in the teaching.
 The way the Buddha handles this incident shows the proper use of the teachings
 on the aggregates: not as a metaphysical theory, but as a tool for questioning
 clinging and so gaining release.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 110: Cula-punnama Sutta — The Shorter Discourse on the Full-moon Night
 {M iii 20} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to recognize — and become — a person of integrity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 111: Anupada Sutta — One After Another {M iii 25} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A description of how insight can be developed either while in, or immediately
 after withdrawing from, the different levels of jhana.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 116: Isigili Sutta — The Discourse at Isigili {M iii 68} [Piyadassi].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha enumerates the many paccekabuddhas who lived on Isigili mountain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 117: Maha-cattarisaka Sutta — The Great Forty {M iii 71} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the nature of noble right concentration, and its interdependence with
 all the factors of the noble eightfold path.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 118: Anapanasati Sutta — Mindfulness of Breathing {M iii 78} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the most important texts for beginning and veteran meditators alike,
 this sutta is the Buddha's roadmap to the entire course of meditation practice,
 using the vehicle of breath meditation.
 The simple practice of mindfulness of breathing leads the practitioner
 gradually through 16 successive phases of development, culminating in full
 Awakening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 119: Kayagata-sati Sutta — Mindfulness Immersed in the Body {M iii 88}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This sutta serves as a companion to the Anapanasati Sutta[Thanissaro].
 and explains the importance of establishing a broad awareness of the body
 in meditation to develop jhana.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 121: Cula-suññata Sutta — The Lesser Discourse on Emptiness {M iii 104}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha instructs Ven.
 Ananda on the practice that leads to the "entry into emptiness," the doorway
 to liberation.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 122: Maha-suññata Sutta — The Greater Discourse on Emptiness {M iii 109}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha instructs Ananda on several practical aspects of the meditative
 dwelling in emptiness, a mode of awareness that can ultimately bring the
 meditator to the threshold of Awakening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 125: Dantabhumi Sutta — The Discourse on the "Tamed Stage" {M iii 128}
 [Horner].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By analogy with the taming of an elephant, the Buddha explains how he tames
 his disciples.
 [BB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 126: Bhumija Sutta — To Bhumija {M iii 138} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Does the desire for Awakening get in the way of Awakening? According to
 this discourse, the question of desiring or not desiring is irrelevant
 as long as one develops the appropriate qualities that constitute the path
 to Awakening.
 The discourse is also very clear on the point that there are right and
 wrong paths of practice: as a geographer might say, not every river flows
 to the sea.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 131: Bhaddekaratta Sutta — An Auspicious Day {M iii 187} [Ñanananda |
 Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this stirring discourse the Buddha underscores the vital urgency of keeping
 one's attention firmly rooted in the present moment.
 After all, the past is gone, the future isn't here; this present moment
 is all we have.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 135: Cula-kammavibhanga Sutta — The Shorter Exposition of Kamma {M iii
 202} [Thanissaro | Ñanamoli].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do some people live a long life, but others die young? Why are some
 people born poor, but others born rich? The Buddha explains how kamma accounts
 for a person's fortune or misfortune.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 136: Maha-kammavibhanga Sutta — The Greater Exposition of Kamma {M iii
 207} [Ñanamoli].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha reveals some of the subtle complexities in the workings of kamma.
 [BB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 137: Salayatana-vibhanga Sutta — An Analysis of the Six Sense-media {M
 iii 215} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discussion of the emotions: where they come from, how they function in
 the path of practice, and how they manifest in an awakened person who is
 fit to teach others.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 138: Uddesa-vibhanga Sutta — An Analysis of the Statement {M iii 223}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to attend to outside objects without letting the mind become externally
 scattered, and how to focus in strong states of absorption without becoming
 internally positioned.
 It's not easy, but it can be done.
 [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 140: Dhatu-vibhanga Sutta — An Analysis of the Properties {M iii 237}
 [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A poignant story in which a wanderer, searching for the Buddha, actually
 meets the Buddha without realizing it.
 He recognizes his mistake only after the Buddha teaches him a profound
 discourse on four determinations and the six properties of experience.
 An excellent illustration of the Buddha's statement, "Whoever sees the
 Dhamma sees me." [TB]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 141: Saccavibhanga Sutta — Discourse on The Analysis of the Truths {M
 iii 248} [Piyadassi | Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Sariputta gives a detailed elaboration on the Buddha's teaching of the
 Four Noble Truths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 143: Anathapindikovada Sutta — Instructions to Anathapindika {M iii 258}
 [Olendzki (excerpt) | Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Sariputta offers a deep teaching on non-clinging to the ailing lay-follower
 Anathapindika.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 146: Nandakovada Sutta — Nandaka's Exhortation {M iii 270} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ven.
 Nandaka discusses impermanence with a large group of nuns, driving his
 point home with particularly vivid similes.
 It must have been an effective teaching: soon afterwards, these nuns all
 become enlightened.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 147: Cula-Rahulovada Sutta — The Shorter Exposition to Rahula {M iii
 277} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Buddha leads his son, Ven.
 Rahula, to arahantship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 148: Chachakka Sutta — The Six Sextets {M iii 280} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How the contemplation of the six senses leads to an understanding of not-self
 and, ultimately, to Awakening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 149: Maha-salayatanika Sutta — The Great Six Sense-media Discourse {M
 iii 287} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How a clear understanding of the six senses leads to the development of
 the Wings to Awakening and to final release.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MN 152: Indriya-bhavana Sutta — The Development of the Faculties {M iii
 298} [Thanissaro].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What qualifies as full mastery of the senses?
\end_layout

